Let X be compact and C ⊆ X be closed. Let {Uᵢ}ᵢ∈I be an open cover of C, where each Uᵢ is open in X (the relatively open case reduces to this by extending each open set of C to an open set of X whose intersection with C gives it).

Since C is closed, V := X \ C is open in X. Then {Uᵢ}ᵢ∈I ∪ {V} is a collection of open sets covering X: every x ∈ C lies in some Uᵢ, and every x ∉ C lies in V.

By compactness of X, there is a finite subcover. Discarding V if it appears, we obtain finitely many Uᵢ₁, …, Uᵢₙ whose union together with V covers X. Since V ∩ C = ∅, the sets Uᵢ₁, …, Uᵢₙ must cover C.

Thus every open cover of C admits a finite subcover, so C is compact. ∎